  <h2 id="what-is-black-diesel">What is Black Diesel?</h2>

  <p>Dolphin Centrifuge, based in Warren, Michigan, supplies purpose-built disc stack centrifuge systems for this application at 60 Gs with separation down to 0.5 microns. Black diesel is an <strong>alternative fuel</strong> produced by processing used motor oil, transmission fluid, and other waste petroleum products. When properly purified, black diesel can be used as a direct substitute for conventional diesel fuel in many applications.
  </p>

  <p>
    Used motor oil contains valuable hydrocarbons that retain most of their original energy content. However, it also accumulates metallic wear particles, carbon soot, water, and chemical contaminants during service. The challenge in producing black diesel lies in removing these contaminants to a level suitable for combustion without damaging engines or violating emissions standards.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    Dolphin Centrifuge supplies complete black diesel purification systems &mdash; from small 2 GPM manual-clean units to high-capacity 40 GPM self-cleaning centrifuge modules with pre-heaters and PLC controls.
  </blockquote>

  <h2 id="purification-methods">Purification Methods</h2>

  <h3>Settling and Filtration</h3>

  <p>
    Traditional methods rely on gravity settling tanks and multi-stage filtration. While simple and inexpensive, settling is extremely slow and cannot remove fine metallic particles or emulsified water. Filters clog quickly when processing used oil due to the high sludge content, resulting in frequent element replacements and inconsistent fuel quality.
  </p>

  <h3>Disc Stack Centrifuge Separation</h3>

  <p>
    A <strong>disc stack centrifuge</strong> generates forces exceeding <strong>7,000 Gs</strong> &mdash; thousands of times greater than gravity. At these forces, even sub-micron metallic particles and emulsified water droplets are driven outward and separated from the clean oil. The result is a consistently high-quality fuel stream regardless of the incoming oil condition.
  </p>

  <p>
    Unlike filters, centrifuge performance does not degrade over time. There are no consumable filter elements to replace, and the centrifuge handles variable contamination levels without adjustment.
  </p>

  <h2 id="centrifuge-operation">Centrifuge Operation for Black Diesel</h2>

  <p>
    The disc stack centrifuge operates as a <strong>three-phase separator</strong>. Used oil is fed continuously into the rotating bowl, where centrifugal force separates it into three distinct phases:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Clean oil (light phase):</strong> Purified black diesel exits through the light-phase outlet at the center of the bowl</li>
    <li><strong>Water (heavy phase):</strong> Separated water and water-soluble contaminants discharge through the heavy-phase outlet at the bowl periphery</li>
    <li><strong>Sludge (solid phase):</strong> Metallic particles, carbon, ash, and other solids accumulate at the bowl wall</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Self-cleaning models automatically eject accumulated sludge at timed intervals without stopping the machine. The <strong>self-ejecting bowl mechanism</strong> opens momentarily to discharge sludge, then closes and resumes full separation &mdash; enabling continuous, unattended operation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Separation efficiency reaches <strong>0.5 microns</strong> for metallic particles and approximately 1.0 microns for non-metallic contaminants, far exceeding what filtration can achieve.
  </p>

  <h2 id="applications">Applications</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Vehicular fuel:</strong> Purified black diesel for trucks, heavy equipment, and fleet vehicles</li>
    <li><strong>Diesel generators:</strong> Alternative fuel for standby and continuous-duty power generation</li>
    <li><strong>Heating fuel:</strong> Replacement for #2 heating oil in boilers and furnaces</li>
    <li><strong>Industrial burners:</strong> Fuel for kilns, dryers, and other thermal processing equipment</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The economics of black diesel are compelling: used motor oil is typically available at low or negative cost (waste haulers pay to have it removed), while the resulting fuel displaces conventional diesel at market prices.
  </p>

